2.1 Specifications of Data Tidying

In my original .csv file, I had encoded NA’s as “.” which was done long before I took this class and is in general a bad idea. I then used find and replace to replace . with NA which then took away my decimal places. I remedied this before bringing in the data. When I initially brought in the data, there were no decimals in pH and protein so I included stringsasfactors = TRUE in my data import. I then changed the procedure type, 60 day rejection, recurrent effusion, and infection to factor varibles. The other variables were characterized correctly.

5 Task 4: Code Book

The data includes a number of variables, some of which are not included in this analysis:

Variable Type Details
studyid ID Study ID
gender categorical male or female (1 = female, 0 = male)
age quantitative age in years
lung_dx categorical diagnosis leading to lung transplant
proc_bil_1 categorical type of procedure, 1 = bilateral lung transplant, 0 = single lung transplant
thoratime quantitative time in days to first thoracentesis
rej_60 categorical acute rejection by biopsy within 60 days of transplant, 1 = yes, 0 = no
recurrent_eff categorical presence of repeated pleural effusions, 1 = yes, 0 = no
infxn_1stthora categorical was infection present in pleural fluid, 1 = yes, 0 = no
volume quantitative volume in mL removed at thoracentesis
wbc quantitative number of white cells in pleural fluid per high power field
pmn quantitative percent of neutrophils in pleural fluid per high power field (0-100%)
lymph quantitative percent of lymphocytes in pleural fluid per high power field (0-100%)
ldh quantitative value of lactate dehydrogenase in pleural fluid, units IU/L
protein quantitative value of protein in pleural fluid, units g/dL
ph quantitative pH value of pleural fluid
timetodc quantitative time to discharge in days

6 Task 5: My Subjects

The data describes a sample of 130 patients who were found to have a pleural effusion after 2 weeks following lung transplant. The two questions for this dataset are: 1. What factors influence the time to pleural effusion? 2. What factors influence the development of acute cellular rejection? The lung transplant community believes that there may be an association between presence of pleural fluid and rejection although this has been poorly studied.

7 Task 6: My Variables:

  • Of note, I have included more variables then I intend to use, but these may be useful for further analysis, so I kept them in here. I am happy to remove them for the final project if you prefer.

gender: Missing 0. Levels (2): Male, Female. female or male.

age: Missing 0. Range: 17-79 Units: Years. Age at time of lung transplant

lung_dx: Missing 0. Levels (6): The indication for lung transplant, typically a lung disease such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) (30%), idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) (48.5%), cystic fibrosis (CF) (13.1%), sarcoidosis (2.3%), Pulmonary hypertension (1.5%) or bronchiectasis (4.6%).

proc_bil_1: Missing 0. Levels (2): The type of transplant procedure, there are two options, bilateral (71.5%) or single (28.5%). Bilateral is typically done in younger and more fit patients.

thoratime: Missing 0. Range: 14-928 Units: Days. Time from lung transplant to thoracentesis (procedure where fluid is drained from the pleural space surrounding the lung)

rej_60: Missing 0. Levels (2), 71.5% with no rejection, 28.5% with rejection. The presence of acute cellular rejection, diagnosed by bronchoscopic biopsy

recurrent_eff: Missing 0. Levels (2), 62.3% without recurrent effusion, 37.7% with recurrent effusion. Did the patient have more than one episode of pleural effusion?

infxn_1stthora: Missing 0. Levels (2), 85.4% without infection, 14.6% with infection. Was there an infection at the time of pleural fluid sampling?

Volume: Missing 4. Range: 1-2000 Units: mL The volume removed in mL of pleural fluid during the thoracentesis.

wbc: Missing 7. Range: 61-100000, Units: per HPF. The number of white cells in pleural fluid per high power field. Higher WBC are concerning for infection.

pmn: Missing 5. Range:0-93, Units: percent. The % of neutrophils in WBC in pleural fluid. Higher PMN (a subset of WBC) are concerning for infection.

lymph: Missing 5. Range 0-98, Units: percent. The % of lymphocytes in WBC in pleural fluid. Can be associated with rare causes of pleural effusion such as certain infections and may be seen in higher numbers in pleural effusions associated with rejection.

Ldh: Missing 6. Range: 0-12853, Units: IU/L. The value of lactate dehydrogenase in pleural fluid. This is used in determining if fluid is a transudate or an exudate which is an important diagnostic classification for pleural effusions.

pH: Missing 9. Range 6.89-7.64, Units: pH units. Measure of acidity of pleural fluid.

protein: Missing 7 Range: 0-4.9, Units: g/dL. The value of protein in pleural fluid. This is used in determining if fluid is a transudate or an exudate which is an important diagnostic classification for pleural effusions.

timetodc: Missing 0. Range: 4-198, Units: Days. Time to discharge in days after lung transplant.

8 Task 7: My Planned Linear Regression Model

The quantitative variable that will be my outcome is time to thoracentesis. Categorical predictor variables include lung disease (multi-categorical), age (quantitative), bilateral procedure (categorical), and time to discharge (quantitative).

9 Task 8: My Planned Logistic Regression Model

The binary variable that will be my outcome is rejection at sixty days (1= yes, 0 = no). Candidate predictors include lung disease (multi-categorical), time to thoracentesis (quantitative), presence of infection (categorical), and lymphocyte percentage (quantitative).

The 0 transformation (log) is not significantly worse than the original data and is a good choice because of our right-skewed data.

model.orig <- lm(thoratime ~ lung_dx + age + proc.bil + timetodc, data=pleural2)
model.sqrt <- lm(log(pleural2$thoratime) ~ lung_dx + age + proc.bil + timetodc, data=pleural2)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(model.orig, which = 1, caption = "Y vs. Predictors Plot")
plot(model.sqrt, which = 1, caption = "Log Y vs. Predictors Residual Plot")

The residual values look slightly better in the log residual plot.

15 Spearman ρ2 plot

For the outcome time to thoracentesis, Spearman ρ2 plot shows that lung diagnosis (lung_dx) may be helpful and perhaps bilateral procedure (proc.bil) and maybe age would be helpful. I thought about adding a spline, but this won’t be helpful with a categorical variable and our quantitative variables are less important in this plot.

plot(spearman2((log(thoratime)) ~ lung_dx + age + proc.bil + timetodc, data = pleural2))

16 2 predictor model

Our R^2 worsens in the new model (0.116 -> 0.062) like due to the loss of predictors but adjusted R2 is stable in the new model (0.058-> 0.055) however they remain very small. The p-value is not statistically significant for either model but improves with the smaller model (m.B). AIC improves from 388 to 382 and BIC from to 417 to 390. In validation for m.B, our R squared is abysmal at 0.042 and our MSE is 1.1253. The new model is now statistically significant compared to the full model for 4 predictors.
